<section id="fightrules">
    <h1>Fight scenes are streamlined and snappy at Quigley...</h1>
    <ul class="row">
        <li class="col-m-6">
            <h3>You may only do one aimed attack per round.</h3>
            <p>An aimed attack is an attack which is specifically directed at a certain area of the body: a punch to the face, a shotgun blast to the knee, a magic missile straight to the chest, a handful of sand in the eyes. One exception is that you may do two aimed attacks in a round immediately following rolling a 20 on defense. These may be aimed at the same target.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="col-m-6">
            <h3>You may do more than one broad attack per round.</h3>
            <p>A broad attack is an attack which doesn't specify a specific part of the body: shooting at someone with a gun at a distance, blindly punching at someone, a wild slash with a sword, tossing a handful of knives at someone. A broad attack may still badly hurt a character depending on the defense roll, but the player simply has more control over where the blow lands.</p>
        </li>
    </ul>
    <ul class="numofattacks row">
        <li class="col-m-6">
            <h3>You may attack each target once per round, up to three attacks.</h3>
            <p>If you are fighting multiple opponents, you may attack each opponent once per round. But you still may only attack one of them with an aimed attack. So, if you were fighting three people, you could try cutting off one opponent's arm, and then slash your sword at the other two without specifying a specific area of their body. Keep in mind it isn't always realistic to maximize this; for example, a character may not be close enough to attack every opponent in the fight. Additionally, you are limited to a total of three attacks, so if you are fighting a gang of four people, you'll only be able to attack three of them at best.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="col-m-6">
            <h3>A highly destructive attack may not be coupled with additional attacks.</h3>
            <p>If your attack stands to hurt several people at once or completely destroy a single target, such as throwing a grenade, spraying a crowd with a flamethrower, firing a missile, or sending a magical fireball in someone's general direction, then you can only do one of these types of attacks per round - with no other attacks.</p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="fightdice">

    <ul class="row">
        <li class="col-m-9">
            <h3>Dice decide whether or not you are hit.</h3>
            <p>You can read all about the dice system <a href="#">on its own page</a>. Specifically concerning fighting, though, here's what you need to know. <strong>If you roll a 1</strong>, you may not attack at all during the following round. <strong>If you roll a 20</strong>, you may do two aimed attacks in a single round - even against a single target. <strong>This means they will have to roll two defense rolls</strong>, rather than the normal one. Certain circumstances may affect your roll's outcome positively or negatively - <strong>up to a modifier cap of plus or minus 3</strong>. That means even if you have negative statuses that would amount to more than 3, you only have to take -3. <strong>Status effects may come with additional rules</strong>, so be sure to read the list below.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="col-m-3 hidden-s hidden-xs">
            <img src="/Css/images/temp/d20.png" />
        </li>
    </ul>

</section>

